{
  "local_port": 55878,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am a Canadian student in grade 11, and want a summer job over seas. What should I do?",
  "response": "That\u2019s an awesome goal! Working overseas as a Canadian Grade 11 student can be a rewarding experience to gain cultural exposure, independence, and work experience. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you plan:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Decide on Your Goals**\n   - **Type of Work**: Do you want a paid job, volunteer work, or an internship?\n   - **Location**: Which country or region interests you? Popular options for Canadian students include European countries, Australia, or even Asian countries like Japan or South Korea.\n   - **Duration**: How long do you want to work abroad? (e.g., 1-2 months or the entire summer.)\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Explore Programs for Youth**\nLook for international programs that cater to high school students. Some options include:\n   - **Work and Travel Programs**: Organizations like [SWAP Working Holidays](https://www.swap.ca/) help Canadians find short-term work abroad, especially in countries like Australia, New Zealand, or the UK.\n   - **Volunteer Abroad Programs**: Programs like [Projects Abroad](https://www.projects-abroad.org/) or [Global Vision](https://globalvision.ca/) offer opportunities for youth to volunteer overseas.\n   - **Language Exchange Programs**: If you\u2019re interested in learning a language, consider programs like [AFS Intercultural Programs](https://afs.org/) or [CIEE](https://www.ciee.org/).\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Check Visa and Permit Requirements**\n   - Research the visa or work permit requirements for the country you\u2019re interested in. Some countries allow youth to work or volunteer on specific visas.\n   - Programs like SWAP often assist with visa applications.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Build Your Skills and Resume**\n   - Highlight any relevant skills (e.g., customer service, tutoring, sports coaching, or languages) on your resume.\n   - Consider getting certifications (e.g., First Aid, lifeguarding, or TEFL) if they\u2019re relevant to the job you want.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Save Money**\n   - Working abroad may be expensive initially due to flights, visas, and accommodation. Start saving early and research affordable destinations.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Connect with Organizations**\n   - Reach out to organizations or companies in your desired country to inquire about opportunities.\n   - Join Facebook groups or forums for Canadians working abroad to get tips and leads.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Prepare for the Experience**\n   - Research the culture, language, and customs of your destination.\n   - Ensure you have travel insurance and necessary vaccinations.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Stay Safe**\n   - Choose reputable programs and organizations.\n   - Keep your family informed about your plans and stay in touch while abroad.\n\n---\n\n### Examples of Summer Jobs Abroad for Students:\n   - Au pair or babysitting (e.g., in Europe or the USA).\n   - Teaching English or tutoring (e.g., in Asia or Latin America).\n   - Farm work or hospitality jobs (e.g., in Australia or New Zealand).\n   - Volunteer work in conservation, education, or community development.\n\n---\n\nStart planning early, as some programs have application deadlines. Best of luck\u2014it\u2019s an amazing opportunity to grow and explore the world!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
